  "prompt": "How do I identify and differentiate a Ghazal and a Hindi Kavita (poem)?",
  "response": "Identifying and differentiating between a **Ghazal** and a **Hindi Kavita** (poem) can be done by understanding their unique structures, themes, and stylistic elements. Here are some key features to help you distinguish between the two:\n\n---\n\n### **Ghazal**:\n1. **Structure**:\n   - Composed of independent couplets called **sher** (each couplet is a complete thought).\n   - Typically has 5-12 couplets, though it can vary.\n   - Each couplet must stand alone in meaning but remain thematically connected to the others.\n\n2. **Rhyme and Meter**:\n   - Follows a strict rhyme scheme: **AA BA CA DA EA**, etc. (the second line of each couplet rhymes).\n   - The first couplet (**matla**) sets the rhyme and refrain (**radif**).\n   - The last couplet (**maqta**) often includes the poet\u2019s pen name (**takhallus**).\n\n3. **Themes**:\n   - Focuses on themes of love (often unrequited), longing, separation, and philosophical musings.\n   - Emotional and reflective in tone.\n\n4. **Language**:\n   - Originated in Persian and Arabic poetry but is widely written in Urdu, Hindi, and other languages.\n   - Uses Persian and Urdu vocabulary extensively.\n\n5. **Example**:\n   > \"\u0939\u0930 \u090f\u0915 \u092c\u093e\u0924 \u092a\u0947 \u0915\u0939\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u094b \u0924\u0941\u092e \u0915\u093f \u0924\u0942 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0939\u0948  \n   > \u0924\u0941\u092e\u094d\u0939\u0940\u0902 \u0915\u0939\u094b \u0915\u093f \u092f\u0947 \u0905\u0902\u0926\u093e\u091c\u093c-\u090f-\u0917\u0941\u092b\u093c\u094d\u0924\u0917\u0942 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0939\u0948\"  \n   > \u2013 Mirza Ghalib\n\n---\n\n### **Hindi Kavita (Poem)**:\n1. **Structure**:\n   - More flexible in structure, with no fixed rhyme or meter.\n   - Can be composed of stanzas, free verse, or prose poetry.\n   - Lines are often part of a larger narrative or theme.\n\n2. **Themes**:\n   - Covers a wide range of themes, including nature, social issues, philosophy, and personal emotions.\n   - Themes can be modern, traditional, or experimental.\n\n3. **Language**:\n   - Written in Hindi or regional Indian languages.\n   - Uses simpler, more accessible vocabulary compared to Ghazals.\n\n4. **Example**:\n   > \"\u092e\u0948\u0902 \u0914\u0930 \u092e\u0948\u0902, \u090f\u0915 \u0905\u0928\u0935\u0930\u0924 \u092f\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0927,  \n   > \u092e\u0948\u0902 \u0914\u0930 \u092e\u0948\u0902, \u090f\u0915 \u0905\u0902\u0924\u0939\u0940\u0928 \u0938\u0902\u0918\u0930\u094d\u0937\u0964\"  \n   \u2013 Dushyant Kumar\n\n---\n\n### **Key Differences**:\n| **Aspect**          | **Ghazal**                         | **Hindi Kavita**                     |\n|----------------------|------------------------------------|--------------------------------------|\n| **Structure**        | Strict couplets with rhyme scheme | Flexible, can be free verse or stanzas |\n| **Themes**           | Love, longing, philosophy         | Wide-ranging, including social issues |\n| **Language**         | Persian, Urdu influence           | Simpler Hindi vocabulary             |\n| **Rhyme and Meter**  | Strictly follows a pattern        | May or may not rhyme                 |\n\nBy focusing on these aspects, you can easily identify and differentiate between a Ghazal and a Hindi Kavita.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
